post_text: We love our Rockwell City first responders! While today's unplanned evacuation was determined to be a false alarm, it was a good opportunity to put our emergency plans and responses to the test. It was a matter of a few short minutes before they were there to assist. Thanks, too, to our hospitable neighbor-- the Methodist Church-- for letting us come in out of the cold rain. We hope we never have an actual emergency, but it's comforting to know we are prepared and protected if we do.

post_text:
We love visitors! But, COVID precautions and unfinished construction are putting limits on our hospitality.

At this time, visitors are not allowed except understand certain circumstances. Please call ahead to make sure you'll be able to enter the building. You will be required to wear a mask, to have your temperature taken, and to answer the standard screening questions.

For those who do need to come into the school, the best option is to park somewhere along Lake Street. You'll need to walk all the way to the west side where the main entrance used to be and enter through the temporary plywood door. That will take you right into the new office area where we can assist you.

Update: These will be used as spacers between children who hold one end of each sock to keep kids farther apart while moving. Hopefully we can do dances outside. Socks will only be used by one child then washed. That's why we need lots‚Äîas many as 200 a day!

Mrs. Panning is on the hunt for socks to use for folk dancing (so kids won't be holding hands). They don't have to be new, but should be clean. Longer is better (like crew style athletic socks). Mismatched, holes, colors . . . we will use them all! There will be a basket at open house. Or send them with your child on the first day. Email Mrs. Panning with questions. The kids and I thank you!!

Dear SCC Elementary Family,

I hope you are all enjoying your summer. Mrs. Stamp and I are back to work now. We are getting everything ready and are so excited for the new year! The construction and remodeling are almost finished at our building, and Ms. Miller and Ms. Bell are going to have the place looking spiffy. I‚Äôm also excited to welcome several new staff members and new students.

Despite COVID, I truly believe this will be an excellent school year. Next week, the district and elementary ‚ÄúReturn to Learn‚Äù plans will be shared with everyone. These plans include measures to address health and safety as well as to provide options for students who can‚Äôt atten in person.

ÔøºÔøºÔøºI can‚Äôt wait to see you all again. If for some reason your family is not planning on face-to-face instruction at school, please call, text, or email me to talk about options so we can plan and be well-prepared.

Thanks,
Mrs. McChesney
712-210-5168
nmcchesney@scc.k12.ia.us

This will be our last week for videos until the fall. We thought it would be fun to get students involved instead of staff this time. Thank you so much to all of the parents that helped me put this together.

The task was, choose 2 of the 8 questions and have your child answer them. The two questions today are:
What do you miss most about school?
and
What do you miss most about your teacher?

I will be posting 2 videos each day this week. Don't forget to check back each day to watch them. Share them with your kids and families. :)

Thanks again to everyone that answered my request for help.
-Mrs. Klaassen

Calling all RC-L Wildcats and all Titans, past and present! Not only has our school year ended in an unexpected way, but so have the careers of two very special educators. Mrs. McAlexander and Mrs. Wuebker are retiring at the conclusion of this school year. We aren't able to recognizing their contributions or celebrate them the way we had hoped, but you can help us. Let's flood their mailboxes with cards of thanks and appreciation for how they have poured themselves into the lives and hearts of so many children. Cards can be sent to:

* Keri McAlexander

417 Austin Street

Rockwell City, IA 50579

* Andy Wuebker

3224 Marshall Avenue

Rockwell City, IA 50579

And, if you have a special story or memory of them, would you consider emailing it to Mrs. McChesney (nmcchesney@scc.k12.ia.us)? They will be compiled as a special gift. Finally, please share this and help us reach as many people as possible who have been touched by these two teachers.

post_text:
preschool registration for 2020-2021:

Registration forms are due to Mrs. McChesney by 4/17 to ensure your child's spot in fall preschool classes. Forms are available on the school website. If you need them mailed to you, contact Mrs. McChesney (712-210-5168 or nmcchesney@scc.k12.ia.us).

Forms can be returned via email to Mrs. McChesney or via mail to the elementary building at 330 Brower Street, Rockwell City, IA 50579. They can also be dropped off to the high school or middle school buildings during regular business hours. Just push the buzzer, the door will open, and you can drop the paperwork inside in order to maintain social distancing. Outside of business hours, paperwork may be deposited in the mailbox near the delivery dock on the east side of the middle school. Again, contact Mrs. McChesney with any questions about returning forms.

HELP! It's a good problems to have, but it is a problem. Our meat delivery from the Food Bank exceeds the freezer space of our food pantry. We have hams, fish sticks, pork loins, and sliced turkey in addition to pork patties. Other new items include Jif snack bars, microwave mac & ch w/ bacon, yogurt, eggs, bread, pudding mixes, additional canned goods, and powdered milk. The pantry will be open on Friday from 12-2, by appointment, or by delivery. Contact Mrs. McChesney at 712-210-5168 or nmcchesney@scc.k12.ia.us. Remember, there is no paperwork or income requirement. It's just a benefit of being part of the SCC district.

Thanks to the staff (as well as Kenley and Landrey Wuebker) for spending their afternoon putting away the new inventory. Also a big thank you to all of the staff who have helped with deliveries to families. Is SCC the best or what?

post_text:
In addition to the general/school board election on November 5, SCC has included a ballot question to extend the "Revenue Purpose Statement" in the district. State legislation approved last year to extend the one cent sales tax revenues called SAVE until the year 2051. Money from this sales tax are divided evenly across Iowa school districts according to enrollment, generating approximately $900 per students. In order to gain the full benefits of this state extension, local districts have to pass a new "Revenue Purpose Statement." Passing it will allow these funds to keep being used for infrastructure purposes like facilities, technology, and transportation. If the vote fails, the district's maximum receipt of SAVE dollars will not be extended to 2051 unless it is approved at a later date.

Voting "yes" for this DOES NOT raise property or income taxes.

post_text: "It's not what's wrong with you; it's what's happened to you." All of us have had both positive and negative things happen to us. Those experiences affect us as children and shape us as adults in ways science is just beginning to understand-- including our behavior, our mental health, our relationships, and even our physical health. We are working to be individuals, a staff, a school, and a community that knows how to heal the hurts and maximize the positives. There's a strong movement building to equip all of us with the information to understand adverse childhood experiences and the tools to build resiliency and spread hope. This video is a great place to start: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=95ovIJ3dsNk

post_text:
Halloween Safety

All guidance classes talked about 5 safety tips for Trick-or-Treating

1) Stranger Danger-don't go inside a strangers house

2)Costume Safety
Be seen - use a flashlight or glow stick
Use face paint instead of a mask when possible.

3) Street Safety
Look both ways before crossing the street with an adult.
Cross at the crosswalks.
Don't run into the streets.

4) Personal Safety
Bring an adult with you.
Stay in a group.
Use the sidewalks.

5) Candy Check
Have an adult check your candy.
Don't eat unwrapped candy or homemade items - you could be allergic to something in them.

It is the only one that is set up correctly with our security system. (2) Please remember to stop in the office, especially if someone other than Mrs. Stamp buzzes you in. (3) If you are taking your child home early, please make sure the office knows so we have accurate attendance information. (4) Consider coming for lunch some day. Kids love having guests for lunch time!

post_text: We have a new, easier way for families to make use of the elementary food pantry! Each month, an order form will be available in the school office and here on Facebook. Families just fill out the order form and return it to the elementary office (or to a Lake City preschool teachers). If a printed form is not available, families can text or email their orders to Mrs. McChesney. Requested items will be boxed up for pick-up. Limited delivery is also available. Here's this month's form. Hungry kids can't learn to the best of their abilities. The food pantry exists to help families who are experiencing short-term or long-term difficulties with their grocery budget. There are no income guidelines or paperwork. Please call the elementary office (712-297-8621) or Mrs. McChesney (712-210-5168) with questions.

post_text:
Many generous community members have asked about needed items for the food pantry and/or supplies for students. We can't tell you how much we appreciate knowing that so many people care about our kids and families!

Here are a few things that are most needed: Titan t-shirts, milk, cereal, butter, cheese, frozen breakfast items, easy to make meals (i.e. Hamburger Helper), ground beef, healthy snacks, peanut butter, jelly, laundry soap, dish soap, toilet paper, shampoo, grocery sacks and reusable shopping bags. The pantry is stocked the 3rd Thursday of the month but gets pretty empty by the first of the month.

Storage space is still an issue for now, so please call, text, or email Mrs. McChesney before bringing a donation. (712-297-8621, 712-210-5168, or nmcchesney@scc.k12.ia.us).

We currently have plenty of school supplies, backpacks, socks, underwear, coats, hats, and mittens, so we aren't needing any donations of these items at this time.
